TASK_TYPE=research
TASK_DESCRIPTION=Deep research into the Charmbracelet ecosystem (Bubble Tea, Bubbles, Lip Gloss, Gum) for building a live heartbeat task list in Go TUI. Covers official apps, component patterns, polling/subscription architecture, styling, community examples, and performance best practices.
TASK_TAGS=research,tui,go,charmbracelet,task-8-dependency
TASK_TEAM=W1
TASK_LOG_1774819619=DISPATCHED: Phase 1 research to W1.1 freelancer
TASK_LOG_1774830100=BUBBLE_TEA_CORE_ARCHITECTURE: Bubble Tea follows The Elm Architecture with three methods: Init() tea.Cmd, Update(tea.Msg) (tea.Model, tea.Cmd), View() tea.View. In v2, View() returns a tea.View struct (not string) via tea.NewView(content). tea.Msg is a type alias for uv.Event. tea.Cmd is func() tea.Msg — a function performing IO that returns a message. Commands run in goroutines automatically. The framework uses a single-threaded event loop for state updates with concurrent command execution — no locks needed in application code. Import path is now charm.land/bubbletea/v2.
TASK_LOG_1774830101=TEA_TICK_AND_TEA_EVERY: tea.Tick(d time.Duration, fn func(time.Time) tea.Msg) tea.Cmd — fires once after duration d using time.NewTimer. tea.Every(duration, fn) — aligns ticks to system clock boundaries (truncates to clock intervals). Both are one-shot; must re-issue from Update() to create recurring ticks. Pattern: define tickMsg type, create tickCmd() that returns tea.Tick(1*time.Second, func(t time.Time) tea.Msg { return tickMsg(t) }), call from Init() and from the tickMsg handler in Update(). For heartbeat dashboard: use tea.Tick(1*time.Second, ...) for 1Hz polling. Re-issue on each tick.
TASK_LOG_1774830102=TEA_BATCH_AND_SEQUENCE: tea.Batch(cmds ...tea.Cmd) tea.Cmd — executes multiple commands concurrently, no ordering guarantee on results. tea.Sequence(cmds ...tea.Cmd) tea.Cmd — runs commands sequentially, one after another. Use Batch in Init() to start tick + initial data load simultaneously. Use Sequence when order matters (e.g., read config then start polling). Both use internal compactCmds helper that filters nil commands.
TASK_LOG_1774830103=PROGRAM_SEND_EXTERNAL_MESSAGES: Program.Send(msg tea.Msg) safely injects messages into the event loop from external goroutines. This is key for fsnotify integration — start a watcher goroutine, on file change events call p.Send(fileChangedMsg{path}). The Send method uses the internal p.msgs channel. Will not block or panic if program has already terminated. Alternative: return a tea.Cmd that blocks on a channel and returns a message when data arrives.
TASK_LOG_1774830104=BUBBLES_LIST_ITEMDELEGATE: The list.ItemDelegate interface has 4 methods: Render(w io.Writer, m list.Model, index int, item list.Item), Height() int, Spacing() int, Update(msg tea.Msg, m *list.Model) tea.Cmd. Item interface requires only FilterValue() string. DefaultItem adds Title() and Description(). DefaultDelegate implements ItemDelegate with state-aware rendering (selected, dimmed, filter-matched). For heartbeat dashboard: implement custom ItemDelegate that renders task rows with status icons, spinner for active tasks, progress bars, and conditional coloring. Height() should return 2-3 for multi-line task items.
TASK_LOG_1774830105=BUBBLES_SPINNER: spinner.Model has Spinner (animation def), Style (lipgloss.Style), frame counter, id, and tag fields. Available types: Line, Dot, MiniDot, Jump, Pulse ("█▓▒░"), Points, Globe, Moon, Monkey, Meter, Hamburger, Ellipsis. Internal tick uses tea.Tick(m.Spinner.FPS, ...) with ID+tag to ensure messages reach correct spinner instance. TickMsg contains Time, ID, tag. For heartbeat: use spinner.Dot or spinner.Pulse for active/busy tasks. Embed spinner.Model in task item struct. Each active task gets its own spinner instance with unique ID.
TASK_LOG_1774830106=BUBBLES_PROGRESS: progress.Model uses spring-based animation (harmonica library) for smooth transitions. Key methods: SetPercent(p float64) tea.Cmd (animated), ViewAs(percent float64) string (static render). Construction: progress.New(progress.WithScaled(true), progress.WithColors(pink, yellow)). Custom fill chars: WithFillCharacters(full, empty rune). Color gradient: WithColors(...color.Color) or WithColorFunc(fn ColorFunc) for dynamic color per percentage. For heartbeat: use ViewAs() for static renders inside list items (no animation needed per-item), or use a single animated progress for overall completion.
TASK_LOG_1774830107=BUBBLES_TABLE: bubbles/table has Model with cols []Column, rows []Row, cursor, styles. Column{Title string, Width int}. Row is []string. Styles struct has Header, Cell, Selected fields. Rendering: selected row gets styles.Selected.Render(). Limited — no per-row conditional styling built in. ALTERNATIVE: lipgloss/table package has StyleFunc(row, col int) lipgloss.Style for full conditional styling per cell. BETTER ALTERNATIVE: evertras/bubble-table — interactive table with sorting, filtering, pagination, zebra striping via style functions, per-cell/row/column styling, frozen columns, horizontal scrolling. For heartbeat: use either custom list with ItemDelegate (more flexible) or evertras/bubble-table (more features). Custom list is recommended for the rich per-item rendering needed.
TASK_LOG_1774830108=BUBBLES_VIEWPORT: viewport.Model manages scrollable content with yOffset/xOffset. Key methods: SetContent(string), SetContentLines([]string), GotoBottom(), ScrollUp(n), ScrollDown(n), AtBottom() bool. Has StyleLineFunc for per-line styling. Auto-scroll: SetContentLines auto-calls GotoBottom() when offset exceeds new max. MouseWheelEnabled flag. SoftWrap support. HighlightStyle for search matches. For heartbeat: use viewport for log/detail panel if showing task output. GotoBottom() for auto-follow mode.
TASK_LOG_1774830109=LIPGLOSS_LAYOUT_COMPOSITION: lipgloss.JoinHorizontal(pos lipgloss.Position, strs ...string) — joins strings side-by-side along vertical axis (pos: 0=top, 0.5=center, 1=bottom). lipgloss.JoinVertical(pos, strs...) — stacks vertically (pos: 0=left, 0.5=center, 1=right). lipgloss.Place(width, height int, hPos, vPos lipgloss.Position, str string) — places content in whitespace. For heartbeat dashboard layout: JoinVertical(lipgloss.Left, header, JoinHorizontal(lipgloss.Top, taskList, detailPanel), statusBar). This creates a header-body-footer layout with horizontal split in body.
TASK_LOG_1774830110=LIPGLOSS_CONDITIONAL_COLORING: AdaptiveColor{Light: "236", Dark: "248"} auto-detects terminal background. CompleteColor{TrueColor: "#0000FF", ANSI256: "86", ANSI: "5"} specifies exact values per color profile — no degradation. CompleteAdaptiveColor combines both. lipgloss/table StyleFunc(row, col int) lipgloss.Style enables per-cell conditional styling. For heartbeat status colors: define style constants — greenStyle for healthy/done (lipgloss.Color("#43BF6D")), yellowStyle for slow/busy (lipgloss.Color("#FDFF8C")), redStyle for stuck/error (lipgloss.Color("#FF5F87")). Apply conditionally in ItemDelegate.Render() based on task status.
TASK_LOG_1774830111=LIPGLOSS_TABLE_STYLEFUNC: lipgloss/table (not bubbles/table) supports StyleFunc for conditional rendering. Pattern: table.New().Border(lipgloss.ThickBorder()).BorderStyle(borderStyle).StyleFunc(func(row, col int) lipgloss.Style { switch { case row == table.HeaderRow: return headerStyle; case row%2 == 0: return evenRowStyle; default: return oddRowStyle } }).Headers("COL1", "COL2").Rows(data...). Can check data values inside StyleFunc to color rows by status. For heartbeat: if using table layout instead of list, this enables status-based row coloring.
TASK_LOG_1774830112=UNICODE_SPARKLINES_AND_INDICATORS: Unicode block characters for custom visualizations: Full blocks "█▓▒░" for density/progress. Braille patterns (U+2800-U+28FF) for sparklines. Box drawing "─│┌┐└┘├┤┬┴┼" for borders. Arrows "▲▼◀▶" for trends. Circles "●○◉◎" for status dots. Custom sparkline: map values to braille height chars "⣀⣄⣤⣦⣶⣷⣿". For heartbeat indicators: "●" green=healthy, "●" yellow=slow, "●" red=stuck, "○" gray=idle. Pulsing: alternate between "●" and "○" using spinner tick. Mini progress: use "▏▎▍▌▋▊▉█" (1/8th block increments) for inline progress bars.
TASK_LOG_1774830113=COMPONENT_COMPOSITION_PATTERN: Root model contains child models as struct fields. Root Init() returns tea.Batch of child Init() commands. Root Update() routes messages to relevant children, collecting commands. Root View() composes child View() outputs using lipgloss.Join*. Pattern: type model struct { taskList list.Model; spinner spinner.Model; detail viewport.Model; width, height int }. In Update: always forward WindowSizeMsg to all children. Use type switches on custom messages to route to specific children. Commands from children are batched: return m, tea.Batch(cmd1, cmd2). Key insight: parent reassigns child model after update (m.taskList, cmd = m.taskList.Update(msg)).
TASK_LOG_1774830114=SOFT_SERVE_TUI_PATTERNS: Soft-serve uses hierarchical component architecture. Central "UI Model" as state manager. Tab-based navigation (README, Files, Commits, Refs, Stash). Custom ItemDelegates: FileItemDelegate, LogItemDelegate, StashItemDelegate — each renders its domain-specific content. Data loaded on-demand from backend, not polled. SSH-accessible TUI uses custom lipgloss renderer per connection for correct color profile detection. Key lesson: delegate rendering to specialized components, keep UI Model as coordinator.
TASK_LOG_1774830115=LAZYGIT_ARCHITECTURE: Uses controller-based pattern (not Bubble Tea — uses gocui). Separates interaction logic from presentation. Maintains GuiRepoState per repository in RepoStateMap. ContextCommon aggregates dependencies. State management across multiple panels. Key lesson for heartbeat: maintain per-task state objects, use a state map keyed by task ID, separate data fetching from rendering concerns.
TASK_LOG_1774830116=FILESYSTEM_POLLING_VS_FSNOTIFY: Two approaches for watching /tmp/doey/ status files. (1) Polling with tea.Tick: simple, predictable, works everywhere. Read status files every 1s in a tea.Cmd. Cost: ~10-50 file reads/second for 10-50 panes. Negligible on modern systems. (2) fsnotify: event-driven, instant detection, lower CPU. Start watcher goroutine, use Program.Send() to inject fileChangedMsg. Complexity: need to handle watcher setup, recursive watching, debouncing rapid events. RECOMMENDATION: Start with tea.Tick polling at 1s interval. Status files are small (<1KB), reads are cheap. fsnotify adds complexity without meaningful benefit for <100 files. If needed later, add fsnotify as optimization behind same message interface.
TASK_LOG_1774830117=PERFORMANCE_RENDERING: Bubble Tea v2 "Cursed Renderer" based on ncurses algorithm — highly optimized, only redraws changed cells. v0.13.3+ already had line-diff optimization (only changed lines redrawn). Automatic color downsampling to terminal capabilities. View() is called after every Update() — keep it fast. lipgloss.Render() cost is proportional to string length, not screen size. String concatenation in View() is the main cost — use strings.Builder for complex views. Recommendation: pre-compute styled strings that don't change (headers, borders) once and cache them. Only rebuild dynamic content (task status, progress) per frame.
TASK_LOG_1774830118=PERFORMANCE_BUDGET: For 1Hz polling dashboard: Update() should complete in <1ms (just update model fields). View() should complete in <5ms for smooth rendering. File reads: os.ReadFile on /tmp/doey/ files takes ~0.1ms each. For 20 status files: ~2ms total read time per tick. JSON parsing: encoding/json on small status structs: ~0.05ms each. Total per-tick budget: ~5ms for data, ~5ms for render = 10ms of 1000ms budget = 1% CPU. Memory: keep model allocations stable — reuse slices, avoid creating new strings every frame where possible. Long-running: no memory leaks if model size is bounded (fixed number of tasks).
TASK_LOG_1774830119=DEBOUNCING_STRATEGIES: Bubble Tea has no built-in debouncing. Patterns: (1) Coalesce in Update: on rapid messages, set a dirty flag, only re-read files on next tick. (2) Timer-based: on first change event, start a 100ms timer. If more events arrive before timer fires, reset. On timer fire, do actual refresh. Implementation: type debounceMsg struct{}; on file change, if !m.debouncing { m.debouncing = true; return m, tea.Tick(100*time.Millisecond, func(time.Time) tea.Msg { return debounceMsg{} }) }. (3) For polling approach: debouncing is inherent — you only read once per tick interval.
TASK_LOG_1774830120=V1_VS_V2_DECISION: Bubble Tea v2 is available (charm.land/bubbletea/v2) with major improvements: View returns tea.View struct, Cursed Renderer for performance, native clipboard, enhanced keyboard. v1 (github.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea) is stable and widely used. Bubbles v2 at charm.land/bubbles/v2. Key v2 changes: View() returns tea.View not string, import paths changed to charm.land/*, KeyMsg split into KeyPressMsg/KeyReleaseMsg. RECOMMENDATION: Use v2 for new development — it's production-ready and the performance improvements matter for a live dashboard. The API changes are straightforward.
TASK_LOG_1774830121=FSNOTIFY_BUBBLETEA_INTEGRATION_PATTERN: If using fsnotify, the pattern is: (1) Create watcher in a tea.Cmd returned from Init(). (2) The cmd blocks on watcher.Events channel in a select loop. (3) On event, return a fileChangedMsg to Update(). (4) In Update(), handle fileChangedMsg by re-reading the changed file and updating model. Code pattern: func watchFiles(dir string) tea.Cmd { return func() tea.Msg { w, _ := fsnotify.NewWatcher(); w.Add(dir); for { select { case ev := <-w.Events: if ev.Op&fsnotify.Write != 0 { return fileChangedMsg{ev.Name} } case err := <-w.Errors: return watchErrMsg{err} } } } }. Issue: this only returns ONE message then the cmd completes. Need to restart the cmd or use Program.Send() from a long-running goroutine.
TASK_LOG_1774830122=CUSTOM_ITEMDELEGATE_FOR_HEARTBEAT: Recommended implementation for task list items. struct taskDelegate struct { styles taskStyles }. Height() returns 3 (status line + detail line + spacing). Render writes: line1 = "[icon] TaskName [spinner/progress] [duration]", line2 = "  status: Working on file.go | 42 tool calls". Use lipgloss inline styling: statusIcon := greenDot.Render("●"); title := titleStyle.Render(task.Name); etc. Compose with fmt.Fprintf(w, "%s %s %s\n%s", icon, title, duration, detail). The delegate receives the full list.Model so it can access width for truncation.
TASK_LOG_1774830123=DATA_MODEL_FOR_HEARTBEAT: Recommended task item struct: type TaskItem struct { ID string; Name string; Status string (READY|BUSY|FINISHED|ERROR|RESERVED); Worker string; StartTime time.Time; LastHeartbeat time.Time; ToolCalls int; FilesChanged []string; Progress float64; Output string }. Implement list.Item: FilterValue() returns Name. Read from /tmp/doey/<project>/status/<pane> files and /tmp/doey/<project>/results/<pane>.json. Parse status files: first line is status string, rest is metadata. Results JSON has tool counts, files changed, output summary.
TASK_LOG_1774830124=RECOMMENDED_ARCHITECTURE_FINAL: Component tree: RootModel { HeaderBar (project name, session info, overall progress), TaskListPanel (list.Model with custom taskDelegate), DetailPanel (viewport.Model showing selected task output), StatusBar (key hints, last refresh time, error count) }. Data flow: Init() -> tea.Batch(tickCmd(), loadInitialState()). On tickMsg -> readAllStatusFiles() cmd. On statusUpdateMsg -> update TaskItem slice, list.SetItems(). On list selection change -> update detail viewport. Layout: lipgloss.JoinVertical(Top, header, lipgloss.JoinHorizontal(Top, taskList, detailPanel), statusBar). Sizing: handle WindowSizeMsg, allocate 60% width to list, 40% to detail. Use tea.Tick(1*time.Second) for polling. Each task item rendered by taskDelegate with status-colored icon, inline spinner for BUSY, progress bar for tasks with known completion %. Keyboard: j/k navigate, enter expand detail, q quit, r force refresh. Use Bubble Tea v2 with charm.land imports.
TASK_LOG_1774830125=KEY_CODE_PATTERNS_SUMMARY: (1) Tick loop: func tickCmd() tea.Cmd { return tea.Tick(time.Second, func(t time.Time) tea.Msg { return tickMsg(t) }) }. (2) Async file read: func readStatus(dir string) tea.Cmd { return func() tea.Msg { entries, _ := os.ReadDir(dir); var tasks []TaskItem; for _, e := range entries { data, _ := os.ReadFile(filepath.Join(dir, e.Name())); tasks = append(tasks, parseStatus(data)) }; return statusUpdateMsg{tasks} } }. (3) Compose children: var cmds []tea.Cmd; m.list, cmd = m.list.Update(msg); cmds = append(cmds, cmd); m.viewport, cmd = m.viewport.Update(msg); cmds = append(cmds, cmd); return m, tea.Batch(cmds...). (4) Conditional styling in delegate: var style lipgloss.Style; switch task.Status { case "BUSY": style = busyStyle; case "ERROR": style = errorStyle; case "FINISHED": style = doneStyle; default: style = idleStyle }. (5) Layout: view := lipgloss.JoinVertical(lipgloss.Left, m.headerView(), lipgloss.JoinHorizontal(lipgloss.Top, m.listView(), m.detailView()), m.statusBarView()); return tea.NewView(view).
